{{Orphan|date=December 2013}}
'''Charles Cochrane''' (1807-1855) was a Scottish author, campaigner for the poor in London in the 'hungry 40s' and, in the last years of his life, campaigner against [[Sunday trading]]. Cochrane was born in [[Madras]], the son of [[Basil Cochrane]] who himself was the sixth son of Scottish nobleman and politician [[Thomas Cochrane, 8th Earl of Dundonald]].
1830 saw the publication of Cochranes' ''The Journal of a Tour Made by Senor Juan De Vega, the Spanish Minstrel of 1828-29''<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cochrane|first1=Charles|title=The journal of a tour made by Señor Juan De Vega , The Spanish Minstrel of 1828-9, Through Great Britain and Ireland, A Character Assumed by an English Gentleman|date=1830|publisher=Simpkin and Marshall|location=London}}</ref> which recounted Cochrane's tour of Britain and Ireland disguised as a Spanish minstrel, 'exploiting somewhat belatedly the sympathy felt for Spanish refugees after the French invasion of 1823'.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Fox|first=Celina|title=The Development of Social Reportage in English Periodical Illustration during the 1840s and Early 1850s|journal=Past & Present|date=February 1977|issue=74|pages=90–111|doi=10.1093/past/74.1.90|volume=74}}</ref> Cochrane's ''Spanish Minstrel'' was satirised by [[Henry Mayhew]] in his one act play ''The Wandering Minstrel''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Mayhew|first=Henry|title=The Wandering Minstrel|year=1836|location=London}}</ref>
After the introduction of the harsh poor laws of the 1830s Cochrane became increasingly concerned with responding in a practical way to poverty, deprivation and hunger in London. In 1842 he founded and became President of the National Philanthropic Association and in 1846 he founded the Poor Man's Guardian Society, 'instituted for the purpose of aiding the destitute in their approach for parochial relief, and for securing them the legal and humane dispensation of the Poor-law.' The society attempted to get the support of [[Charles Dickens]] who was cautious in his response but did pay them a subscription of five guineas.<ref>{{cite book|last=Tillotson (ed)|first=Kathleen|title=The Letters of Charles Dickens Volume Four 1844-1846|year=1977|publisher=Clarendon Press|location=Oxford|page=528}}</ref> The organisation described Charles Dickens as a vice-president.<ref>{{cite news|title=Poor Man's Guardian Society|newspaper=London Pioneer pg. 44; Issue 3.|date=May 14, 1846}}</ref> Cochrane became an increasingly prominent figure in London circles with his campaigns for the poor, advocating radical improvements in sanitation and public health.
By 1848 the NPA had introduced a system of paid street cleaners to West Central London<ref>{{cite journal|title=National Philanthropic Society (for the promotion of social and sanitary improvements and the employment of the poor, 40, Leicester-square)|journal=The Lady's Newspaper|date=March 20, 1847|issue=12|page=266}}</ref>
